<bdy>

<b>Relevance Vector Machine (RVMs)</b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../488/233488.xml">
machine learning</link> technique that uses <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../890/4890.xml">
Bayesian theory</link> to obtain sparse solutions for <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../568/26568.xml">
regression</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../244/1579244.xml">
classification</link>. The RVM has an identical functional form to the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../309/65309.xml">
Support Vector Machine</link>, but provides probabilistic classification.<p>

Compared to the SVM the Bayesian formulation allows to avoid the set of free parameters that the SVM have and that usually require cross-validation based post optimizations. However RVMs use a Expectation Maximization(EM) like learning method and are therefore at risk of local minima, unlike the standard <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../378/4456378.xml">
SMO</link> based algorithms employed by <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../910/303910.xml">
SVM</link>s which are guaranteed to find a global optimum.</p>

